data.content:
## Migration Analysis

### Inventory of thread-termination APIs found

| API | Location | Pattern |
|-----|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Blocking call interruption |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop fallback |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | `RunLoop()` | Blocking call that must become cancellation-aware |

Both `Thread.Abort()` (throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`) and `Thread.Interrupt()` (obsolete `SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9) must be replaced with cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken`.

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private readonly object _lock = new object();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns 0 if _newEvent is signaled,
            // 1 if the cancellation token fires.
            int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (index == 1) // cancellation
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            string? item = null;
            lock (_lock)
            {
                if (_queue.Count > 0)
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
            }

            if (item is not null)
                Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();          // wakes RunLoop via token.WaitHandle
        _thread?.Join(5000);    // wait up to 5 s for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

---

### What changed and why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | `Interrupt` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0046`). The cancellation token's `WaitHandle` wakes the blocked thread cooperatively. |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Removed | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. The loop now exits voluntarily via `token.IsCancellationRequested`. |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` | Waits on **both** the event and the cancellation token, so the thread wakes for either new work or shutdown. |
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Loop cooperates with cancellation instead of relying on an externally injected exception. |
| No `IDisposable` | Implements `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEvent` are `IDisposable` and must be cleaned up. |

---

### Pitfalls to watch for

1. **`WaitOne` without the token** — If you keep `_newEvent.WaitOne()` alone, `_cts.Cancel()` will never wake the thread. You **must** use `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle`.

2. **Race condition in the original code** — If multiple `Enqueue` calls fire before the thread wakes, `Set()` is idempotent so only one signal registers. The original code would lose items. The migrated version guards against this with `_queue.Count > 0`.

3. **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** — Leaks internal timer/callback registrations. Always wrap the owner in `IDisposable`.

4. **Assuming cancellation is instant** — If `Handle(item)` is long-running, the thread won't check the token until it finishes. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `Handle` at safe checkpoints if responsiveness matters.

5. **Double-`Stop` safety** — `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` is safe to call multiple times, and `Join` on an already-finished thread returns immediately, so this code is double-call safe.
